Files:
- plugins/newrelic/src/newrelic-api.ts (fix partial error handling at line 46)

Context:
Current code (lines 46-53):
  if (json.errors?.length && !json.data) {
    const msg = json.errors.map(e => e.message).join('; ');
    if (msg.includes('NOT_FOUND')) throw ToolError.notFound(msg);
    if (msg.includes('FORBIDDEN') || msg.includes('Api-Key')) throw ToolError.auth(msg);
    throw ToolError.internal(msg);
  }
  return json.data as T;

The guard `!json.data` means partial responses (data + errors) always return json.data silently. GraphQL partial responses are common for New Relic when NRQL queries partially succeed (some data returned, some fields null with error messages).

Options for the fix (choose the most appropriate):
1. Log errors at warn level: `if (json.errors?.length) { log.warn('GraphQL partial errors', json.errors.map(e => e.message)); }`
2. Include error messages in the return value by wrapping the result
3. Throw if all top-level data fields are null (indicating full failure despite data key being present)

The safest approach that doesn't break existing tools: add `log.warn()` for partial errors. This surfaces them in the audit log without changing the return type.

import { log } from '@opentabs-dev/plugin-sdk' — check if log is already imported.

Constraints:
- Do NOT change the return type of graphql<T>() — tool handlers depend on it returning T
- Do NOT throw on partial errors — some New Relic queries legitimately return partial results (e.g., null fields for entities without data)
- The existing auth/notFound error classification must still work for errors-only responses
